# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ballistic-eyewear
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] **alternate frame sequencing**, **alternate image**, **AI**, **alternating field**, **field sequential** or **eclipse method**) is a technique for displaying stereoscopic 3D images.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Modern active shutter 3D systems generally use liquid crystal shutter glasses (also called "LC shutter glasses" or "active shutter glasses").
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Each eye's glass contains a liquid crystal layer which has the property of becoming opaque when voltage is applied, being otherwise transparent.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The glasses are controlled by a timing signal that allows the glasses to alternately block one eye, and then the other, in synchronization with the refresh rate of the screen.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The timing synchronization to the video equipment may be achieved via a wired signal, or wirelessly by either an infrared or radio frequency (e.g.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Historic systems also used spinning discs, for example the Teleview system.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Active shutter 3D systems are used to present 3D films in some theaters, and they can be used to present 3D images on CRT, plasma, LCD, projectors and other types of video displays.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Although virtually all ordinary unmodified video and computer systems can be used to display 3D by adding a plug-in interface and active shutter glasses, disturbing levels of flicker or ghosting may be apparent with systems or displays not designed for such use.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The rate of alternation required to eliminate noticeable flicker depends on image brightness and other factors, but is typically well over 30 image pair cycles per second, the maximum possible with a 60 Hz display.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] A 120 Hz display, allowing 60 images per second per eye, is widely accepted as flicker-free.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Crosstalk is the leakage of frames between left eye and right eye.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] LCDs have exhibited this problem more often than plasma and DLP displays, due to slower pixel response time.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] LCDs that utilize a strobe backlight, such as nVidia's LightBoost, reduce crosstalk.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] This is done by turning off the backlight between refreshes, while waiting for the shutter glasses to switch eyes, and also for the LCD panel to finish pixel transitions.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The **M-3DI Standard** was a cross-manufacturer standardization initiative to increase compatibility of LC (Active) Shutter Glasses led by Panasonic in collaboration with XpanD 3D and announced in March 2011.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] It aimed to increase acceptance of 3D products by consumers by extending the agreement to various manufacturers of 3D TV, computers, notebooks, home projectors, and cinema hardware.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] As of April 2011, the agreement was joined by Hitachi, Changhong, Funai, Hisense, Mitsubishi Electric, Epson, ViewSonic, and SIM2 Multimedia S.p.A.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In August of the same year, M-3DI was superseded by another agreement, named "**Full HD 3D Glasses Initiative**", formed between Panasonic, Samsung, Sony, Sharp Corporation, TCL Technology, Toshiba and Philips.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The standardization agreement comprised consumer products including televisions, computers and projectors, also based on XpanD 3D's technology.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Field Sequential has been used in video games, VHS and VHD movies and is often referred to as HQFS for DVDs, these systems use wired or wireless LCS glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The Sensio format was used with DVDs using wireless LCS glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Each different active 3D shutter glasses implementation can operate in their own manufacturer-set frequency to match the refresh rate of the display or projector.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Therefore, to achieve compatibility across different brands, certain glasses have been developed to be able to adjust to a broad range of frequencies.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The principle made its public debut remarkably early.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1922, the Teleview 3-D system was installed in a single theater in New York City.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Several short films and one feature-length film were shown by running left-eye and right-eye prints in a pair of interlocked projectors with their shutters operating out of phase.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Each seat in the auditorium was equipped with a viewing device containing a rapidly rotating mechanical shutter synchronized with the projector shutters.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The system worked, but the expense of the installation and the unwieldiness of the viewers, which had to be supported on adjustable stands, confined its use to this one engagement.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In recent decades, the availability of lightweight optoelectronic shutters has led to an updated revival of this display method.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Liquid crystal shutter glasses were first invented by Stephen McAllister of Evans and Sutherland Computer Corporation in the mid-1970s.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The prototype had the LCDs mounted to a small cardboard box using duct tape.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The glasses were never commercialized due to ghosting, but E&S was a very early adopter of third-party glasses such as the StereoGraphics CrystalEyes in the mid-1980s.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Panasonic developed a 3D television that employed active-shutter technology in the late 1970s.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] They unveiled the television in 1981, while at the same time adapting the technology for use with the first stereoscopic video game, Sega's arcade game *SubRoc-3D* (1982).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1985, 3-D VHD players became available in Japan from manufacturers such as Victor (JVC), National (Panasonic), and Sharp.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Other units were available for field sequential VHS tapes including the Realeyes 3-D.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] A few kits were made available to watch field sequential DVDs.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Sensio released their own format which was higher quality than the High Quality Field Sequential (HQFS) DVDs.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The method of alternating frames can be used to render modern 3-D games into true 3D, although a similar method involving alternate fields has been used to give a 3-D illusion on consoles as old as the Master System and Family Computer.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Special software or hardware is used to generate two channels of images, offset from each other to create the stereoscopic effect.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] High frame rates (typically ~100fps) are required to produce seamless graphics, as the perceived frame rate will be half the actual rate (each eye sees only half the total number of frames).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Again, LCD shutter glasses synchronized with the graphics chip complete the effect.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1982, Sega's arcade video game *SubRoc-3D* came with a special 3-D eyepiece, which was a viewer with spinning discs to alternate left and right images to the player's eye from a single monitor.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The game's active shutter 3-D system was developed by Sega with Matsushita (now Panasonic).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1984, Milton Bradley released the 3-D Imager, a primitive form of active shutter glasses that used a motorized rotating disc with transparencies as physical shutters, for the Vectrex.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Although bulky and crude, they used the same basic principle of rapidly alternating imagery that modern active shutter glasses still use.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Nintendo released the Famicom 3D System for the Famicom in October 1987 in Japan, which was an LCD shutter headset, the first home video game electronic device to use LCD Active Shutter glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Sega released the SegaScope 3-D for the Master System Worldwide in November 1987.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Only eight 3-D compatible games were ever released.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1993, Pioneer released the LaserActive system which had a bay for various "PAC's" such as the Mega LD PAC and LD-ROM² PAC.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The unit was 3-D capable with the addition of the LaserActive 3-D goggles (GOL-1) and the adapter (ADP-1).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In 1999–2000, a number of companies created stereoscopic LC shutter glasses kits for the Windows PCs which worked with application and games written for Direct3D and OpenGL 3D graphics APIs.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] These kits only worked with CRT computer displays and employed either VGA pass-through, VESA Stereo or proprietary interface for left–right synchronization.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The most prominent example was the ELSA Revelator glasses, which worked exclusively with Nvidia cards through a proprietary interface based on VESA Stereo.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Nvidia later bought the technology and used it in its stereo driver for Windows.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The glasses kits came with driver software which intercepted API calls and effectively rendering the two views in sequence; this technique required twice the performance from the graphic card, so a high-end device was needed.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Visual glitches were common, as many 3-D game engines relied on 2-D effects which were rendered at the incorrect depth, causing disorientation for the viewer.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Very few CRT displays were able to support a 120 Hz refresh rate at common gaming resolutions of the time, so high-end CRT display was required for a flicker-free image; and even with a capable CRT monitor, many users reported flickering and headaches.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] These CRT kits were entirely incompatible with common LCD monitors which had low 60 Hz or 75 Hz refresh rates, unlike CRT displays that had a higher refresh rate at lower resolutions.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Moreover, the display market swiftly shifted to LCD monitors and most display makers ceased production of CRT monitors in early 2000s, which meant that PC glasses kits shortly fell into disuse and were reduced to a very niche market, requiring a purchase of a used high-end, big diagonal CRT monitor.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] SplitFish EyeFX 3-D was a stereo 3-D shutter glasses kit for the Sony PlayStation 2 released in 2005; it only supported standard-definition CRT TVs.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The kit arrived too late in the product cycle of the console when it was effectively replaced by the PlayStation 3, and only a few games were supported, so it was largely ignored by gamers.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The USB-based Nvidia 3D Vision kit released in 2008 supports CRT monitors capable of 100, 110, or 120 Hz refresh rates, as well as 120 Hz LCD monitors.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] There are many sources of low-cost 3-D glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] IO glasses are the most common glasses in this category.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] XpanD 3D is a manufacturer of shutter glasses, with over 1000 theaters currently using XpanD glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] With the release of this technology to the home-viewer market as of 2009, many other manufacturers are now developing their own LC shutter glasses, such as Unipolar International Limited, Accupix Co., Ltd, Panasonic, Samsung, and Sony.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The M-3DI Standard, announced by Panasonic Corporation together with XPAND 3D in March 2011, aims to provide industry-wide compatibility and standardization of LC (Active) Shutter Glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Samsung has developed active 3D glasses that are 2 ounces (57 g) and utilize lens and frame technology pioneered by Silhouette, who creates glasses for NASA.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Nvidia makes a 3-D Vision kit for the PC; it comes with 3-D shutter glasses, a transmitter, and special graphics driver software.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] While regular LCD monitors run at 60 Hz, a 120 Hz monitor is required to use 3-D Vision.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Other well-known providers of active 3-D glasses include EStar America and Optoma.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Both companies produce 3D Glasses compatible with a variety of technologies, including RF, DLP Link and Bluetooth.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In 2007, Texas Instruments introduced stereo 3-D capable Digital Light Processing (DLP) solutions to its OEMs, Samsung and Mitsubishi then introduced the first 3-D ready DLP televisions, and DLP 3-D projectors came later.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] These solutions utilize the inherent speed advantage of the Digital Micro-mirror Device (DMD) to sequentially generate a high refresh rate for the left and right views required for stereoscopic imaging.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] DLP 3-D technology uses the SmoothPicture wobulation algorithm and relies on the properties of modern 1080p60 DMD imagers.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] It effectively compacts two L/R views into a single frame by using a checkerboard pattern, only requiring a standard 1080p60 resolution for stereoscopic transmission to the TV.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The claimed advantage of this solution is increased spatial resolution, unlike other methods which cut vertical or horizontal resolution in half.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The micromirrors are organized in a so-called "offset-diamond pixel layout" of 960×1080 micromirrors, rotated 45 degrees, with their center points placed in the center of "black" squares on the checkerboard.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The DMD employs full-pixel wobulation to display the complete 1080p image as two half-resolution images in a fast sequence.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The DMD operates at twice the refresh rate, i.e.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] 120 Hz, and the complete 1080p picture is displayed in two steps.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] On the first cadence, only half of the original 1080p60 image is displayed – the pixels that correspond to the "black" squares of the checkerboard pattern.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] On the second cadence, the DMD array is mechanically shifted ("wobulated") by one pixel, so the micromirrors are now in a position previously occupied by the gaps, and another half of the image is displayed – this time, the pixels that correspond to the "white" squares.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] A synchronization signal is then generated to synchronize the screen's refresh with LC shutter glasses worn by the viewer, using Texas Instruments' proprietary mechanism called DLP Link.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] DLP Link keeps sync by embedding briefly-flashed white frames during the display's blanking interval, which are picked up by the LC shutter glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Plasma display panels are inherently high-speed devices as well, since they use pulse-width modulation to maintain the brightness of individual pixels, making them compatible with sequential method involving shutter glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Modern panels feature pixel driving frequency of up to 600 Hz and allow 10-bit to 12-bit color precision with 1024 to 4096 gradations of brightness for each subpixel.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Samsung Electronics launched 3D-ready PDP TVs in 2008, a "PAVV Cannes 450" in Korea and PNAx450 in the UK and the US.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The sets utilize the same checkerboard pattern compression scheme as their DLP TVs, though only at the native resolution of 1360×768 pixels and not at HDTV standard 720p, making them only usable with a PC.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Matsushita Electric (Panasonic) prototyped the "3-D Full-HD Plasma Theater System" on CES 2008.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The system is a combination of a 103-inch PDP TV, a Blu-ray Disc player and shutter glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The new system transmits 1080i60 interlaced images for both right and left eyes, and the video is stored on a 50-gigabyte Blu-ray using the MPEG-4 AVC/H.264 compression Multiview Video Coding extension.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Formerly, LCDs were not very suitable for stereoscopic 3-D due to slow pixel response time.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Liquid crystal displays have traditionally been slow to change from one polarization state to another.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Users of early 1990s laptops are familiar with the smearing and blurring that occurs when something moves too fast for the LCD to keep up.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] LCD technology is not usually rated by frames per second but rather the time it takes to transition from one pixel color value to another pixel color value.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Normally, a 120 Hz refresh is displayed for a full 1/120 second (8.33 milliseconds) due to sample-and-hold, regardless of how quickly an LCD can complete pixel transitions.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Recently, it became possible to hide pixel transitions from being seen, using strobe backlight technology, by turning off the backlight between refreshes, to reduce crosstalk.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Newer LCD televisions, including high-end Sony and Samsung 3D TVs, now utilize a strobed backlight or scanning backlight to reduce 3D crosstalk during shutter glasses operation.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In vision therapy of amblyopia and of intermittent central suppression, liquid crystal devices have been used for purposes of enhanced occlusion therapy.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] In this scenario, the amblyopic patient wears electronically programmable liquid crystal glasses or goggles continuously for several hours during regular everyday activities.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] Wearing the device encourages or forces the patient to use both eyes alternatingly, similar to eye patching, but rapidly alternating in time.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The aim is to circumvent the patient's tendency to suppress the field of view of the weaker eye and to train the patient's capacity for binocular vision.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/active-shutter-3d-system] The goggles mostly feature a much slower flicker rate than the more well-known active shutter 3-D glasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The **Authorized Protective Eyewear List (APEL)** is a list of protective eyewear tested and approved by the U.S.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The APEL includes spectacles and goggles optimized for different situations.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The APEL was created in 2006 because statistics showed that about 10% of battlefield injuries at that time included eye injuries.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The APEL is updated periodically; it usually contains more than a dozen types of non-prescription and prescription spectacles and goggles for different duty situations and soldier preferences.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] In 2010, the **APEL** was placed under the oversight of the Military Combat Eyewear Protection (MCEP) program under the office of PEO Soldier.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The APEL also includes different styles to accommodate soldier preferences, with the goal of increasing the use of eye protection.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Approved protective eyewear includes both military standard and commercial styles.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Soldiers serve in different situations with different types of risk for eye injury, from ballistic projectiles.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Some styles can accommodate prescription lenses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Several types of goggles are available because they are optimized for certain purposes, such as regular use, use in vehicles, or use with night vision goggles.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Some fit over regular eyeglasses, some can accommodate prescription lenses, and others are designed for those who do not wear eyeglasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Eyewear on the APEL must meet the standards established by the Army Vision Conservation and Readiness Program.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] For ballistic resistance, this program requires that eyewear meet the current ANSI Z87 civilian standard.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Then the U.S. military standard (MIL-PRF-31013) must also be met.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The U.S. civilian standard for protective eyewear was revised in 2010.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The previous version from 2003 was organized by the type of protector.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The Z87.1-2010 version is organized by the type of hazard such as droplet and splash, impact, optical radiation, dust, fine dust, and mist.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Also, the 2003 version specified that protective products be marked as providing “Basic” or “High Impact” protection.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] In the Z87.1-2010 standard, there is no longer a distinction between levels of ballistic protection.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Products are either non-impact or impact protectors.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Products marked as impact protectors must pass all high-impact testing requirements and are marked as “Z87+”.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Non-impact protectors are those which do not pass all high-impact testing requirements and are therefore marked only with “Z87” (no “+” sign).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The U.S. military standard (MIL-PRF-31013), requires (at a minimum) that ballistic eyewear can always withstand a 0.15 caliber, 5.8 grain, T37 shaped projectile at a velocity of 640 to 660 feet per second (approximately 3.8 mm 0.376 g at a velocity of 195 – 201 m/s).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Goggles are required to stop a 17-grain fragment simulating projectile moving at a speed of 550 feet per second (approximately twice the energy impact of spectacles).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] For testing, the velocity of the projectile must be verified using sound or optical chronograph methods.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The eyewear is put on an Alderson 50th percentile male headform.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] A 0.002 inch thick aluminum foil “witness sheet” is placed behind the area of impact.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] This sheet shows whether any small pieces penetrate or come off of the eyewear during the test.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The eyewear being tested is hit one time straight on slightly toward the outside of the center of the lens.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] The eyewear fails the test if the aluminum foil witness sheet is punctured or if the eyewear is cracked.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] In addition to ballistic performance, the U.S. military standard includes requirements for optical clarity, protection from UV rays, fit, chemical resistance, and environmental stability (properties won’t be changed by exposure to a range of temperatures or levels of humidity).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/authorized-protective-eyewear-list] Though soldiers are increasingly exposed to explosive threats, there is currently no testing or performance requirements for blast resistance of approved eyewear.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Aviator style sunglasses are intended to be worn under headgear and are characterised by dark, oftentimes reflective lenses and thin monel, steel or titanium metal frames with double or triple bridges and bayonet earpieces or flexible cable temples that hook more securely behind the ears.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The large lenses are not flat but slightly convex.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The design attempts to cover the entire field of vision of the human eye and significantly reduce the amount of transmitted visible light and (near) infrared radiation and prevent (erythemal) ultraviolet radiation from entering the eye from any angle.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] For selecting sunglasses, the United States Federal Aviation Administration has published an aeromedical safety brochure for general aviation pilots, commercial pilots and physicians.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Polarized and photochromic lenses are not recommended for use by pilots.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The UK Civil Aviation Authority has also provided guidance on the use of sunglasses by pilots.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The first aviator style sunglasses contracted by the US military in 1935 were the U.S.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Army Air Corps D-1 Sunglasses made by American Optical.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] They have a conspicuous USAC engraving on the hinged bridge.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The D-1 flying goggle assembly was standardized on 13 August 1935, and was actually a pair of sun glasses with a rigid frame and plastic insulated arms.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The D-1 sunglasses were superseded by the more comfortable AN6531 flying sun glasses (comfort cable) in November 1941.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] In the second half of the 1930s and early 1940s, a group of American firms continued developing sunglasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The military "flying sun glasses (comfort cable)" were standardized in November 1941.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] They were produced in huge quantities (several million pieces) for pilots and sailors.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The lenses were made to a joint standard shared by the U.S.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] As a result, the lens carried an "AN" (Army/Navy) specification number: the AN6531.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Government specified the shape of the lens and the color, which was initially a green tinted lens that transmitted 50% of incoming visible daylight.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] This AN6531 Type 1 lens proved insufficient to protect the pilot's eyes from sun glare so this lens was superseded by the darker AN6531 Type 2 lens in rose smoke.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Various contractors made the frames and ground the lenses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] These included American Optical, Bausch & Lomb, The Chas.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Fischer Spring Co., Willson Optical and Rochester Optical Co.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Frame and hinge design varied slightly from contractor to contractor.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Despite being designed for utility, these glasses had advanced properties: teardrop-shaped and convex lenses, plastic nose pads and a prominent brow bar and featured flexible cable temples.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The nickel plated frame was made of a copper based alloy to prevent offsetting compasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The "teardrop" shape lens of the AN 6531 was designed to accommodate Air Force pilots who were constantly looking down at their instrument panel while in flight, and that influenced all future Aviator style lens shapes.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The AN6531 Comfort Cable aviator sunglasses frame kept being issued by the U.S. military as No.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] MIL-G-6250 glasses after World War II with different lenses as Type F-2 (arctic) and Type G-2 aviator sunglasses but fitted with darker lenses until their substitute the Type HGU-4/P aviator sunglasses became available in the late 1950s.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] After World War II AN6531 Comfort Cable aviator sunglasses were available for civilians on the surplus market.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] In 1929, US Army Air Corps Colonel John A.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Macready worked with Bausch & Lomb, a Rochester, New York-based medical equipment manufacturer, to create aviation sunglasses that would reduce the distraction for pilots caused by the intense blue and white hues of the sky.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Specifically, MacCready was concerned about how pilots' goggles would fog up, greatly reducing visibility at high altitudes.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The prototype, created in 1936 and known as "Anti-Glare", had plastic frames and green lenses that could cut out the glare without obscuring vision.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Impact-resistant lenses were added in 1938.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The sunglasses were redesigned with a metal frame in 1938 and promoted by Bausch & Lomb as the Ray-Ban Aviator.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] According to the BBC, the glasses used "Kalichrome lenses designed to sharpen details and minimise haze by filtering out blue light, making them ideal for misty conditions." In 1936 Ray-Ban had been founded as a civilian division of Bausch & Lomb.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] This style of sunglasses is credited with being one of the first popularized styles of sunglasses to be developed.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] In its military usage, the sunglasses replaced the outmoded flight goggles used previously, as they were lighter, thinner, and "more elegantly designed".
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Aviators became a well-known style of sunglasses when US General Douglas MacArthur landed on a beach in the Philippines in World War II and newspaper photographers snapped several pictures of him in October 1944 wearing them that became a lasting image of the Second World War.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Bausch & Lomb dedicated a line of sunglasses to him in 1987.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The first advertisements for Ray-Ban Aviators stated they would provide "real scientific glare protection" and were sold as sporting equipment.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] At this time, they had not yet taken on their name of "Aviators;" the Second World War had not yet begun.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] During the 1950s, aviator sunglasses were a part of the cultural style, mimicking the military style.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] In addition to popularity in the 1950s, aviators were popular in the 1970s and 1980s, being worn by public figures like Slash, Michael Jackson, George Michael, Tom Cruise, Freddie Mercury, Jeff Lynne, Roger Waters and Elvis Presley.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Besides flexible cable temples and bayonet temples, non-U.S.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Air Force issued glasses often feature traditional skull temples.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Some models have polarized lenses, made of Polaroid polarized plastic sheeting laminated between lenses, to reduce glare caused by light reflected from non-metallic surfaces such as water (see Brewster's angle for how this works) as well as by polarized diffuse sky radiation (skylight).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Besides the standard model there are several different Ray-Ban Aviator sunglasses variations designed as functional, technical and recreational sunglasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The Ray-Ban Shooter variant was introduced in 1938 and the Ray-Ban Outdoorsman variant in 1939.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] These sunglasses both feature a large brow bar above the nose intended to keep sweat and debris from inhibiting the wearer's vision.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The brow bar and temple end pieces of the Shooter and Outdoorsman variants have been covered through years with different materials.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Aimed at the sports enthusiast and outdoorsman, The Ray-Ban Shooter variant incorporates a cigarette holder, a circular device located at the center of the nose bridge originally intended to free the sportsman's hands while taking aim.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] In 1953 Ray-Ban introduced G-15 tempered glass lenses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] These neutral gray/green lenses transmit 15% of incoming visible light whilst providing "true" color and contrast distribution.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] In 1958, American Optical created the Flight Goggle 58 according to the then-new U.S.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Air Force Type HGU-4/P aviator sunglasses standard.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Type HGU-4/P sunglasses feature semi-rectangular lenses with less lens surface area and are lighter compared to the preceding Type G-2 sunglasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The HGU-4/P design frame allowed the visor to reliably clear the aviator's spectacles when a flight helmet is worn, and covers the full field of vision.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The frame additionally features bayonet temples designed to slip under a flight helmet or other headgear and was more compatible with oxygen masks.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] They are commercially known as "Original Pilot Sunglass", and were issued by the U.S. military in 1959 to pilots shortly after the HGU4/P was officially recommended by military optometrists in November 1958.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The HGU-4/P design frame is also issued to military personnel that require various corrective clear or other types of lenses and allows corrected vision through the full field of vision.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] Besides the military, Type HGU-4/P aviator sunglasses were also issued to and used by NASA astronauts.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] By 1982, Randolph Engineering had become the prime contractor for military-style Type HGU-4/P aviation flight glasses for the United States Department of Defense.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] They are commercially known as "Randolph Aviator" sunglasses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] HGU-4/P aviation flight glasses are still built to the guidelines of the MIL-S-25948 military specification, a document detailing the manufacturing specifications.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] One of the many specifications is that the neutral grey lenses used in Type HGU-4/P aviator sunglasses must transmit between 12% and 18% of incoming visible daylight while providing "true" color and contrast distribution.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/aviator-sunglasses] The military HGU-4/P Aviator and the Modified HGU-4/P Apache spectacles intended for Apache attack helicopter aircrew are under regular review to determine their functionality.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Safety glasses, sunglasses and goggles that claim to meet ballistic safety standards are widely available.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Some can accommodate prescription lenses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Although not required, it is recommended that all eyewear meet ANSI Z87.1, but for ballistic protective eyewear it is required that it meets military standards for impact protection (MIL-DTL-43511D clause 3.5.10 for goggles and visors and MIL-PRF31013 clause 3.5.1.1 for spectacles).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Though these standards have been very commonly used especially by NATO forces, an update on MCEPS of January 2013 now reference these clauses in MIL-PRF-32432.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Ballistic sunglasses or prescription eyeglasses must meet the same requirements.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] In brief, the U.S. military standard requires that ballistic eyewear must be able to withstand up to a 3.8 mm (.15 caliber) projectile at 195 m/s (640 ft/s)) for spectacles and 5.6 mm (.22 caliber) projectile at 168–171 m/s (550–560 ft/s) for goggles.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] The European standard identifies four levels of impact protection.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Manufacturers offer a variety of styles and colors to meet different needs and preferences.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Some make claims of superior side protection, comfort, anti-fog coatings, interchangeable lenses, transition lenses, etc.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] At least one product from more than a half dozen manufacturers are listed on the U.S.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Army's Authorized Protective Eyewear List (APEL).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Some options, including the Wiley X PT-1 and Talon as well as Revision's Sawfly and the Desert Locust Goggle can be obtained in prescription lenses that meet the ballistic protection standards.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] In addition to impact requirements, the U.S.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Army requires for its soldiers that ballistic eyewear be functional, reasonably comfortable, not faddish (i.e., no bright colors or distracting designs) and able to be disinfected.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Ballistic eyewear is commercially available for anyone who wishes to buy it.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] People who use ballistic eyewear include those who regularly use firearms or are involved in activities where their eyes or faces may be exposed to small fragments.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] This includes many people who work in manufacturing.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Military personnel may be required to use ballistic eyewear especially when in combat.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Hunters are also frequent users of ballistic eyewear because of the possibility of a ricochet or the recoil of the firearm that may result in injury.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Law enforcement officers also use ballistic eyewear for confrontations.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] There are three standards currently used to test the effectiveness of ballistic eyewear.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Also, the 2003 version specified that protective products be marked as providing "Basic" or "High Impact" protection.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Products marked as impact protectors must pass all high-impact testing requirements and are marked as "Z87+".
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Non-impact protectors are those which do not pass all high-impact testing requirements and are therefore marked only with "Z87" (no "+" sign).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] The U.S. military standard requires (at a minimum) that ballistic eyewear can always withstand a 0.15 caliber, 5.8 grain, T37 shaped projectile at a velocity of 640 to 660 feet per second (approximately 3.8 mm 0.376 g at a velocity of 195 – 201 m/s).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] A 0.002 inch thick aluminum foil "witness sheet" is placed behind the area of impact.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] In addition to ballistic performance, the U.S. military standard includes requirements for optical clarity, protection from UV rays, fit, chemical resistance, and environmental stability (properties won't be changed by exposure to a range of temperatures or levels of humidity).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] The European EN 166 standard identifies four levels of ballistic protection.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] "Increased robustness" (marked S) can withstand a 22 mm steel ball weighing 43 g dropped onto the lens from a height of .38 meters (15 inches).
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] "Low energy impact" (marked F) can withstand a 6mm steel ball weighing 0.86 g and traveling at least 45 m/s at the time of impact.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] "Medium energy impact" (marked B) must be able to protect from a 6 mm 0.86 g steel ball with an impact velocity of 120 m/s.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] "High energy impact" (marked A) must be able to protect from a 6 mm 0.86 g steel ball with an impact velocity of 190 m/s.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] The history of protective eyewear goes back to 1880, when P.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Johnson's design used two layers of semi-opaque cloth.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] He had in mind that firemen, furnace-men and others exposed to intense light would use them to reduce the light intensity.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Fullicks bonded several pieces of glass together.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] It seems that another Englishman, John Crane Woods, had safety in mind when he patented the idea of bonding sheets of transparent cellulose nitrate, using Canadian balsam, between two sheets of glass.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] The product was unsuccessful due to expense, poor quality and lack of demand.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] In 1910, Edouard Benedictus, a French chemist, obtained both French and British patents for the manufacturing of laminated safety glass.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Benedictus used gelatin and other adhesives instead of Canadian balsam in the laminated glass.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] During World War I, laminated glass was used to make small, round lenses in gas masks and for windshields in military motor vehicles and aircraft.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] (For a number of recent years, the DuPont chemical company gave a Benedictus Award for the innovative use of laminated glass in architecture.) In the 1940s, manufacturers figured out how to sand and make safety glasses and goggles for welders, construction workers, and the like.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] In the early 1960s the U.S. government sponsored experiments testing the ballistic performance of various plastics and glass for potential use in eyewear, using tests similar to those required by today's U.S. military standard.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] After this time, polycarbonate became the standard material used for ballistic eyewear.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Investigations since this early work have included examining the effects of manufacturing and layering techniques on the ballistic performance of polycarbonates.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] In the early 1970s, Wigglesworth investigated the ballistic resistance of 3 mm. and 2 mm. thicknesses of allyl resin and tempered glass as a function of the diameter of a small steel ball, impact velocity, and curvature of the lens.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] In 1996, Belkin described new ballistic eyewear that also provided improved protection from injuries caused by laser light reaching the eyes.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] Research into improved protection of the eyes from ballistic threats has continued.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] For example, Kelly presented work investigating layered materials to provide protection from 9 mm automatic gunfire, a much greater level of ballistic protection than previously available.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] While they demonstrated a successful concept, they recognized that advances in manufacturability were still needed for such protective eyewear to be affordable and plentiful.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] In 2006 Hartley et al. were awarded a US Patent for Eyewear for ballistic and light protection.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/ballistic-eyewear] The invention was not for new protective materials but for a system that would allow the easier interchange of lenses between various types of protective devices, such as glasses, goggles and face shields.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/belay-glasses] Belaying involves a person standing on a stable platform below a rock climber controlling the tension and friction of the climber's rope.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/belay-glasses] Since this activity requires craning one's neck to look up at the climber, a common malady named "belayer's neck" can occur.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/belay-glasses] The prismatic lenses of the belay glasses are arranged so as to bend light from above through total internal reflection into the observer's eye, allowing the belayer to observe the climber while maintaining a comfortable head/neck position.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/belay-glasses] The first belay glasses were invented in 2007 by climber Albi Schneider from Germany.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Benjamin Franklin is generally credited with the invention of bifocals.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] One account states that Franklin cut his lenses in half so that he could follow speakers of French at court by reading their lips.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Unless further evidence emerges all we can say for certain is that Franklin was one of the first people to wear split bifocals and this act of wearing them caused his name to be associated with the type from an early date.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] This no doubt contributed greatly to their popularisation.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] The evidence implies, however, that when he sought to order lenses of this type the London opticians were already familiar with them.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Other members of Franklin's circle of British friends may have worn them even earlier, from the 1760s, but it is at best uncertain (and arguably improbable?) that split bifocal lenses had a famous gentleman inventor.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Since many inventions are developed independently by more than one person, it is possible that the invention of bifocals may have been such a case.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] John Isaac Hawkins, the inventor of trifocal lenses, coined the term *bifocals* in 1824 and credited Benjamin Franklin.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] In 1955, Irving Rips of Younger Optics developed the first commercially viable seamless or "invisible" bifocal”, a precursor to progressive lenses.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Beach's 1946 work in "blended lenses", O'Conner's "Ultex" lens in 1910, and Isaac Schnaitmann's single-piece bifocal lens in 1837.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Original bifocals were designed with the most convex lenses (for close viewing) in the lower half of the frame and the least convex lenses on the upper.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Up until the beginning of the 20th century two separate lenses were cut in half and combined in the rim of the frame.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] The mounting of two half-lenses into a single frame led to a number of early complications and rendered such spectacles quite fragile.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] A method for fusing the sections of the lenses together was developed by Louis de Wecker at the end of the 19th century and patented by John Louis Borsch Jr.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Courmettes (1884-1969), a French immigrant to the US, patented the "Flat Top" (or "D Segment") reading portion of the bifocal.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] The advantages were wide reading area, less prismatic effects and no image jump between distance and close viewing.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] This was first introduced in mass production by the Univis Lens Co. of Dayton, OH. in 1926.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] In 1935, Courmettes went on to patent the Tilted Bifocal Lens, in 1936, a method of grinding two prescriptions simultaneously on that Tilted Bifocal Lens, and in 1951, the Cataract Bifocal Lens.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Today most bifocals are created by moulding a reading segment into a primary lens and are available with the reading segments in a variety of shapes and sizes.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Bifocals can contribute to falls and may cause headaches or even dizziness for some wearers.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Adaptation to the small field of view offered by the reading segment of bifocals can take some time, as the user learns to move either the head or the reading material rather than the eyes.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Computer monitors are generally placed directly in front of users and can lead to muscle fatigue due to the unusual straight and constant movement of the head.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] This trouble is mitigated by the use of monofocal lenses for computer use.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Research continues in an attempt to eliminate the limited field of vision in current bifocals.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] New materials and technologies may provide a method which can selectively adjust the optical power of a lens.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/bifocals] Researchers have constructed such a lens using a liquid crystal layer applied between two glass substrates.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blinders-poultry] In pheasants, blinders have been shown to reduce the incidence of birds pecking each other and damage to the feathers or skin.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blinders-poultry] In laying hens, blinders have been shown to reduce feather pecking, improve food utilisation (due to less spillage) and increase egg production.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blinders-poultry] Blinders which require a pin to pierce the nasal septum and hold the device in position almost certainly cause pain to the bird.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blinders-poultry] In the UK, the use of these devices is illegal on welfare grounds.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blinders-poultry] The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs in their Codes of Recommendations for the Welfare of Livestock: Laying Hens, states: "The Welfare of Livestock (Prohibited Operations) Regulations 1982 (S.I.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blinders-poultry] Studies on pin-less blinders indicate these devices are at least temporarily distressful to the birds.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blinders-poultry] In pheasants, fitting blinders causes an increase in head shaking and scratching, and increases in damage to the beak and nostrils of the bird.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blinders-poultry] Fitting pin-less blinders to laying hens leads to reduced activity, increased resting, adjustment problems in feeding, stereotypic head shaking and protracted displacement neck preening for a month after fitting.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blinders-poultry] In another study on laying hens, mortality was greater among hens wearing blinders compared to hens that had been beak-trimmed.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] A **blindfold** (from Middle English **blindfellen**) is a garment, usually of cloth, tied to one's head to cover the eyes to disable the wearer's sight.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] While a properly fitted blindfold prevents sight even if the eyes are open, a poorly tied or trick blindfold may let the wearer see around or even through the blindfold.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] Use of a blindfold is said to enhance the remaining senses of the wearer, focusing attention on sound, smells and physical contact.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] This increased awareness is said to allow for greater excitement and anticipation by eliminating visual cues, as one cannot see what to expect.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] It also requires trust of the submissive, with all the emotional ramifications that entails.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] The blindfold has been a powerful symbol in divination and mythology since the 15th century.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] In law, it is seen being worn by Lady Justice, to represent objectivity and impartiality.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] The blindfold as a symbol is also a common theme in tarot and other divination methods.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] It can represent themes of the victim, resistance to clarity, denial, or limited views.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] It is often accompanied by underlying themes of integrity and truth at a cost.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] Likewise, the icon of the blindfold can symbolize the dichotomy of the conscious and the unconscious, as wearing a blindfold represents a stasis or a lesser state of consciousness, whereas taking off one's blindfold represents a form of awakening or rebirth.
[src:ballistic-eyewear/blindfold] It also represents connection to feeling over senses, emphasizing the importance of emotion over perception.
